{{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = The Reverend | name = Wallace Clift | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!-- Use only if different from full/othernames --> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1926|03|27}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | death_cause = | region = | nationality = American | period = | occupation = Academic | title = | boards = <!-- Board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation --> | known_for = | spouse = [[Jean Dalby Clift]] | children = | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | era = | language = | discipline = Religious studies | sub_discipline = Jungian psychology | religion = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Texas]], [[Harvard University]], [[Church Divinity School of the Pacific]], [[University of Chicago Divinity School]] | thesis_title = Psychological and Biblical-Theological Perspectives on Hope from the Viewpoints of C. G. Jung and John Knox | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | school_tradition = | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = <!--Only those with WP articles--> | main_interests = | workplaces = [[University of Denver]], [[Iliff School of Theology]] | notable_works = ''Jung and Christianity'' (1982) | notable_ideas = | influences = [[Carl Jung]], [[Jolande Jacobi]] | influenced = <!--Must be referenced from a third party source--> | awards = <!--Notable national level awards only--> | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Wallace Bruce Clift, Jr.''' (born March 27, 1926<ref>http://files.usgwarchives.net/tx/coke/vitals/births/cokeb26.txt</ref>) is the author of several books and articles in the field of [[psychology of religion]], and a professor emeritus at the [[University of Denver]], where he chaired the Department of Religion for many years.<ref name=ECD>{{Cite book|year=2009|title=Episcopal Clerical Directory |publisher=Church Publishing|page=180}}</ref> He has lectured and given workshops extensively in the United States, Australia, Europe and Asia on such topics as [[Jungian psychology]], [[Christian theology]], [[pilgrimage]], spiritual growth, [[dream interpretation]], journaling, and the [[Myers-Briggs Type Indicator]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Hallowed Ground: From Graceland to Mother Cabrini Shrine, Modern Pilgrims Journey Far and Wide|first=Linda |last=Castrone |newspaper=[[Rocky Mountain News]] |location=Denver, CO|date=December 24, 1991|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=RM&p_theme=rm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB4D986F2C8BE04&p_field_direct-0=document_id }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Pilgrim's Progress: One Professor's Journey to Enlightenment|first=Charlotte |last=Legg |newspaper=University of Denver Today |location=Denver, CO|date=October 15, 1990}}</ref> Clift has published six books, three of which were co-authored with his wife, the Reverend [[Jean Dalby Clift]].<ref name=Crossings />
==Early career and education== Clift earned a [[bachelor's degree]] with honors in economics and government from the [[University of Texas at Austin]] in 1949.<ref name=Crossings /> Clift then went on to earn a law degree at [[Harvard Law School]] in 1952, and practiced law at [[Baker, Botts, Andrews and Parish]] in [[Houston, Texas]], before attending [[seminary]].<ref name=Crossings /> He married another attorney at the firm, Jean Dalby, in 1954.<ref name=ECD /> In 1960, he earned an [[M.Div.]] from the [[Church Divinity School of the Pacific]].<ref name=Crossings /> Ordained deacon in 1960 and priest in 1961, Clift served as vicar of Grace Church and the Church of the Resurrection in Houston until 1964.<ref name=ECD /> While in Houston, Clift attended the major address by then-presidential candidate Senator John F. Kennedy to the Greater Houston Ministerial Association on September 12, 1960 regarding Kennedy's ability to make decisions independent of the Roman Catholic Church, and is viewable on the 1:38 mark in the recorded video of the address.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jfklibrary.org/Asset-Viewer/ALL6YEBJMEKYGMCntnSCvg.aspx#ooid=NzZzJ4MTqoXZCUpwn6QYqueiGyWPFKV0|title=Address of Senator John F. Kennedy|accessdate=2012-10-21}}</ref>
In 1964, Clift received a Farish Foundation grant to study the psychology of [[Carl Jung]].<ref name=ECD /> He studied from 1964 to 1966 at the [[C. G. Jung Institute in Zürich]], Switzerland, where he worked with analyst [[Jolande Jacobi]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Clift|first=Wallace|year=1982|title=Jung and Christianity: The Challenge of Reconciliation|publisher=The Crossroad Publishing Company|pages=xi|isbn=0-8245-0409-7}} {{Cite book|last=Clift|first=Wallace|year=1990|title=Journey Into Love: Road Signs Along The Way|publisher=The Crossroad Publishing Company|pages=11–12 |isbn=0-8245-1032-1}}</ref> He earned his Ph.D. from the [[University of Chicago Divinity School]] with his dissertation ''Psychological and Biblical-Theological Perspectives on Hope from the Viewpoints of C. G. Jung and John Knox''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Psychological and Biblical-Theological Perspectives on Hope from the Viewpoints of C.G. Jung and John Knox|first=Wallace|last=Clift|year=1970 | publisher=Unpublished Ph.D. Dissertation, University of Chicago| oclc=43671150}}</ref>
==Academic career== Clift taught psychology of religion at the [[University of Denver]] from 1969 to 1992, and in 1981 helped start its joint Ph.D. program in religious and theological studies with the [[Iliff School of Theology]].<ref name=ECD /><ref>Iliff and DU Joint Ph.D. Program.{{cite web|url=http://www.du.edu/duiliffjoint/ |title=The Joint Ph.D Program|accessdate=2010-10-14}}</ref> Clift co-founded the C. G. Jung Society of Colorado in 1976, and served as its first president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jungsocietyofcolorado.org/history.htm | publisher=C. G. Jung Society of Colorado|title=History |accessdate=2010-09-25}}</ref> After his retirement from the University of Denver in 1992, Clift was appointed Canon Theologian of the Episcopal Diocese of Colorado and invited to head the Anglican Studies program at St. Thomas Theological Seminary.<ref name=AnglicanStudies1>{{Cite journal|title=Anglican studies program celebrates ten years |first=Wallace |last=Clift | date=June–July 1998|magazine=Colorado Episcopalian|volume=60|page=11}} {{Cite book|year=2007|title=Episcopal Clerical Directory |publisher=Church Publishing|page=174}}</ref> When St. Thomas closed in 1995, Clift and the Episcopal diocesan bishop negotiated the Anglican Studies program's move to the Methodist Iliff School of Theology, where Clift continued to head the program for another seven years.<ref name=AnglicanStudies1 />
==Professional recognition== In 2000, Bette Lanning endowed the Wallace B. and Jean Dalby Clift Scholarship Fund at Iliff to provide funds for students enrolled in its Anglican Studies Program.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=DU's Anglican Studies to Celebrate 10th Anniversary |first=Gregory |last=Robbins |page=5 | date=January–February 2006|magazine=Colorado Episcopalian|volume=68|url=http://www.coloradodiocese.org/06_newsandevents/PDFs/epis_jan_feb_06.pdf }}</ref> [[Church Divinity School of the Pacific]] awarded Clift an honorary doctorate in 2003.<ref name=Crossings>{{Cite journal|title=2003 Alumni/ae Convocation |pages=13–14 | date=Winter 2003|magazine=Crossings|publisher=[[Church Divinity School of the Pacific]] |url= http://www.cdsp.edu/docs/crossings/CDSP_Crossings_Fall-Winter03.pdf |accessdate=2010-10-15}}</ref> Clift served as President of the Standing Committee of the [[Episcopal Diocese of Colorado]] from 1989 to 1990<ref name=ECD /> and is Canon Theologian Emeritus of the diocese.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Clergy Directory |publisher=[[Episcopal Diocese of Colorado]] | url=http://www.coloradodiocese.org/02_findachurch/clergy_directory.html#c | accessdate=2010-09-15}}</ref>
